### JavaScript Timers

**Timers** let you schedule code to run **after a delay** or at **regular intervals**.

---

### `setTimeout()` -- Run Once After Delay

```js
const timerId = setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("This runs after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);

// Cancel the timeout
clearTimeout(timerId);
```

---

### `setInterval()` -- Run Repeatedly

```js
const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
  console.log("This runs every 1 second");
}, 1000);

// Stop the interval
clearInterval(intervalId);
```

---

### Practical Examples

#### Countdown Timer

```js
let count = 5;
const timer = setInterval(() => {
  console.log(count);
  count--;
  if (count < 0) {
    clearInterval(timer);
    console.log("Done!");
  }
}, 1000);
```

#### Debounce (delay execution until user stops typing)

```js
let timeout;
input.addEventListener("input", () => {
  clearTimeout(timeout);
  timeout = setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("User stopped typing");
  }, 300);
});
```

---

### `requestAnimationFrame()` -- Smooth Animations

A better alternative for **animations** -- it syncs with the monitor's refresh rate (typically 60fps):

```js
function animate() {
  // Update animation
  element.style.transform = `translateX(${x}px)`;
  x++;
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);
}

requestAnimationFrame(animate);
```

| Feature | `setInterval` | `requestAnimationFrame` |
|---------|---------------|------------------------|
| **Purpose** | General repeated tasks | Smooth animations |
| **Pauses when tab hidden** | No | Yes (saves battery) |
| **FPS** | Fixed (unreliable) | Matches screen refresh |

---

> **Key Point:** Timer delays are **minimum** delays. The actual delay may be longer if the main thread is busy with other tasks.

  **Time Precision:** All timer delays are in **milliseconds** (1000 ms = 1 second).

codeExample:
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => console.log("After 1s"), 1000);

let count = 0;
const interval = setInterval(() => {
  count++;
  console.log(`Tick ${count}`);
  if (count >= 3) clearInterval(interval);
}, 500);

console.log("End");
